<div class="maintext">
  <h1 id="biography" class="text-center" padding-bottom="60px" id="Biography"><b>Biography</b></h1>
  <p></p>
   <p>Edvard Hagerup Grieg is one of the greatest if not the greatest icons of Norway. Grieg was born on Jun, 15 1843 to a merchant father and a mother who was a musical teacher. Grieg showed an affinity to music from a young age. His talent was developed by his mother until he enrolled at the Conservatory of Leipzig in the fall of 1858 at the recommendation of a distant relative named Ole Bull who was a renowned violinist. Grieg initially had a lot of trouble adjusting at his school in Leipzig and this reflected in his poor grades. Grieg survived pleurisy and pneumonia that left his left lung collapsed in 1860. This affected his health for the rest of his life. Grieg went on to graduate from the Leipzig Conservatory with excellent grades and as a noted musician.
  </p>
  <p>
Grieg left for Copenhagen in 1863, where he would live for the next three years. Copenhagen was the art and cultural hub of Scandinavia at the time and Grieg hoped to develop himself as a composer here. He wrote a symphony at the encouragement of fellow composer Niels Gade. Although the symphony was instrumental in the development of his technical skills, Grieg did not want it to ever be performed.
  </p>
  <p>
Grieg married Nina Hagerup in 1867. Grieg’s greatest breakthrough came in 1868 with his composition of his piano concerto in A minor.
Although he mostly composed in German romantic styles during his earlier years, Grieg desperately wanted to develop music with a Norwegian identity. Most of his productive times as a composer were during the summer when he had more time. Grieg had a wooden cabin by the majestic landscapes of the settlement of Ullensvang. Grieg also brought a piano to his log cabin so that he could work on his compositions almost full time here.

 <table style="float:right; margin-left:5px; margin-right:5px;">
   <tr><td>
 <img class="ullensvang" src="https://s8.postimg.org/j11ocv1kl/Grieg15.jpg" alt="The Settlement of Ullensvang" width="601.5px" height="400px" align="right"></tr></td>
  <tr style="font-family:calibri; font-size:18px"><td class="ullenscaption">The landscape of Ullensvang with the modern Hotel of Ullensvang in the foreground</td></tr>
  </table>

 His autobiographer Aimer Gronvold wrote about the fact that Grieg was greatly inspired by the landscapes and people around him while he composed at his summer dwelling.
  </p>
  <p>
The Peer Gynt suites, which are one of Grieg’s trademark compositions, were started in 1874 as an incidental music to the plays Peer Gynt by Henrik Ibsen. The author himself requested Grieg to make the compositions. During his most productive years, Grieg went all over Europe on performance tours. His travels allowed him to meet other famous composers including Liszt, Brahms, Tchaikovsky and Clara Schumann.
  </p>
  <p>
From 1880 to 1882, Grieg served as the musical director of the Bergen Philharmonic. Grieg remained a renowned composer of his time in his later years and received a retirement pension from the Norwegian government. Edvard Grieg passed away on Sep. 4, 1907 after suffering a heart attack and being admitted to a municipal hospital in Bergen. His funeral was attended by over 40,000 people and was marked by his own composition of a funeral march. The funeral march had been written earlier for the funeral of his friend and fellow composer, Rikard Nordraak.
  </p>
<div class="row">
<div class="col-md-6"><img src="https://s29.postimg.org/p8r9dvo0n/Grieg7.jpg" alt="Grieg's Composer's Cabin" width="598.5px" height="450px">
<figcaption class="griegcaption cabincaption">Grieg's "Composer's Cabin" in Ullensvang just outside Bergen</figcaption>
</div>

<div class="col-md-6">
<img class="imagealign" style="align:right" src="https://s8.postimg.org/wvsilq9zp/Grieg8.jpg" alt="Edvard Grieg and Nina Hagerup" width="636px" height="400px">
<figcaption class="griegcaption">Edvard Grieg and Nina Hagerup</figcaption>

</div>
